What is the difference between Aegopodium a plant genus of the carrot family Apiaceae native to Europe and western Asia and Clitoria? Aegopodium and Clitoria are two different plant genera belonging to different families. Aegopodium is a member of the carrot family Apiaceae, while Clitoria is a member of the Fabaceae or legume family. Additionally, Aegopodium is a perennial herb, while Clitoria is a vine. The flowers of Aegopodium are compound umbels visited by insect pollinators, while Clitoria has insect-pollinated flowers that are pea-like in appearance. Finally, the fruit of Aegopodium consists of two-winged or ribbed nuts, while Clitoria produces legumes or pods that contain seeds.
